ng of   Griffith  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Griffith","meanings":["Welsh (Carmarthenshire and western England): from the Old Welsh personal name <i>Gruffudd</i>, Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, composed of the elements <i>grip</i>, of uncertain significance, + <i>iud</i> ‘chief, lord’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William ap Gruffudd was born in 1030, in Wales as the son of Gruffydd ap Owain. He had at least 1 son."},"et":{"1030–":"1030–Surnud","1012–Male":"1012–Surnud","1030–Male":"1030–Surnud","1060–Male":"1060–Surnud","0995–Male":"0995–Surnud","0995":"0995","1012":"1012","1030":"1030","1060":"1060","Wales":"Wales"},"fi":{"1030–":"1030–Kuollut","1012–Male":"1012–Kuollut","1030–Male":"1030–Kuollut","1060–Male":"1060–Kuollut","0995–Male":"0995–Kuollut","0995":"0995","1012":"1012","1030":"1030","1060":"1060","Wales":"Wales"},"fr":{"1030–":"1030–Décédé","1012–Male":"1012–Décédé","1030–Male":"1030–Décédé","1060–Male":"1060–Décédé","0995–Male":"0995–Décédé","0995":"0995","1012":"1012","1030":"1030","1060":"1060","Wales":"Galles","lifeSummary":"William ap Gruffudd est né en 1030, à Galles, fils de Gruffydd ap Owain. Il a eu au moins 1 fils."},"de":{"1030–":"1030–Verstorben","1012–Male":"1012–Verstorben","1030–Male":"1030–Verst